#!/bin/sh
# Forces the HDMI output to 1280x720@60, and keeps enforcing it for the
# entire session - not just once at login.
#
# Why this is needed: the Magewell capture card's EDID advertises
# 1920x1080 as its preferred mode, and labwc negotiates its own output
# mode from EDID at startup - it ignores a `video=` kernel cmdline
# override (tried first, confirmed ineffective across a reboot: labwc
# re-picks "preferred" every time regardless of what cmdline.txt says).
# Setting the mode from inside autostart, after the compositor is
# already up, is what actually sticks.
#
# The Cyclone IV bitstream's image-processing IPs (sharpening, lane
# detection) use a fixed line-buffer width sized for 1280 columns. Feed
# them a 1920-wide signal instead and every ~1280 columns the buffer's
# internal position wraps early relative to the real scanline - visible
# as a black frame or a 3-way tiled/repeated image on those experiments
# (1920/1280 = 1.5, matching the observed tiling). Experiment 1
# (inverting) has no line buffer, so it looked fine at either
# resolution and gave no hint the output was wrong - and on a stuck
# 1080p session, the extra 640x360 the picture doesn't cover shows the
# Pi's own desktop background instead of the experiment.
#
# Deploy to ~/.config/labwc/autostart on the Pi (chmod +x). See
# README.md's "HDMI output resolution" section.
#
# A bounded retry-then-give-up loop (this script's previous version)
# is not enough. Confirmed in the field 2026-07-24: labwc had been
# running for over a day, the connector read "connected" the whole
# time (so this was NOT the separate disconnected-on-boot race - see
# README's "second failure mode" and config.txt.append), yet the
# session was still stuck at 1920x1080. The output evidently only
# became available *after* the fixed retry window (a couple of
# minutes) had already elapsed that boot, so the old script had
# already exited by the time there was anything to correct - and
# nothing was left watching afterwards. There's also no reason the
# mode can only drift once, at boot: anything that makes the
# Magewell's EDID get re-read mid-session (a USB reset on the capture
# card, its own driver reload, etc.) would silently flip the Pi back
# to 1920x1080 with no supervisor watching for the rest of that
# session.
#
# So this now runs for the whole graphical session instead of a fixed
# window: poll the current mode, and the instant it isn't 1280x720,
# force it back. Idle cost is one `wlr-randr` call every 5s -
# negligible - and it self-heals any future recurrence of this same
# bug, at boot or mid-session, without needing a fresh login to
# re-trigger it. flock guards against two copies stacking up if
# autostart ever runs twice without a fresh boot (e.g. a compositor
# restart) - the second one exits immediately instead of adding a
# redundant loop.
(
	flock -n 9 || exit 0
	while true; do
		if ! wlr-randr 2>/dev/null | grep -q '1280x720 px, 60.000000 Hz (current)'; then
			wlr-randr --output HDMI-A-1 --mode 1280x720@60 2>/dev/null
		fi
		sleep 5
	done
) 9>/tmp/hdmi-force-720p.lock &
